dir=\"auto\"\u003eMDN:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eIn comparison to the global \u003ccode\u003eisNaN()\u003c/code\u003e function, \u003ccode\u003eNumber.isNaN()\u003c/code\u003e doesn't suffer the problem of forcefully converting the parameter to a number. This means it is now safe to pass values that would normally convert to \u003ccode\u003eNaN\u003c/code\u003e, but aren't actually the same value as \u003ccode\u003eNaN\u003c/code\u003e. This also means that only values of the type number, that are also \u003ccode\u003eNaN\u003c/code\u003e, return true. \u003ca data-canonical-src="https://badges.gitter.im/Join%20Chat.svg" style="max-width: 100%;"></a></p><p dir="auto">Lodash and Underscore are great modern JavaScript utility libraries, and they are widely used by Front-end developers. However, when you are targeting modern browsers, you may find out that there are many methods which are already supported natively thanks to ECMAScript5 [ES5] and ECMAScript2015 [ES6]. If you want your project to require fewer dependencies, and you know your target browser clearly, then you may not need Lodash/Underscore.</p><p dir="auto">You are welcome to contribute with more items provided below.</p><ul dir="auto"><li><p dir="auto">If you are targeting legacy JavaScript engine with those ES5 methods, you can use <a href="https://github.com/es-shims/es5-shim">es5-shim</a></p></li><li><p dir="auto">Please note that, the examples used below are just showing you the native alternative of performing certain tasks. For some functions, Lodash provides you more options than native built-ins. This list is not a 1:1 comparison.</p></li><li><p dir="auto">Please send a PR if you want to add or modify the code. No need to open an issue unless it's something big and you want to discuss.</p></li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Voice of Developers</h2><a id="user-content-voice-of-developers" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: Voice of Developers" href="#voice-of-developers"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><blockquote><p dir="auto"><a href="https://twitter.com/codylindley/status/692356631007342593" rel="nofollow">Make use of native JavaScript object and array utilities before going big.</a></p></blockquote><blockquote><p dir="auto">—Cody Lindley, Author of <a href="http://shop.oreilly.com/product/9780596159788.do" rel="nofollow">jQuery Cookbook</a> and <a href="http://shop.oreilly.com/product/0636920027713.do" rel="nofollow">JavaScript Enlightenment</a></p></blockquote><blockquote><p dir="auto"><a href="https://twitter.com/daniellmb/status/692200768556916740" rel="nofollow">You probably don't need Lodash.
